text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Expansion: Perfective Done Historically Seen as Marker of Class%0a:Author: AlexisA%0a:Original: [[Articles.MorphosynaticDiversityOfThePerfectiveDone|MorphosynaticDiversityOfThePerfectiveDone]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.jess_smith|jess_smith]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 29.03.2021 - 11:01%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210421-175616-584610#%0a* [-21.04.2021 - 10:56-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210421-175616-584610#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI found this really interesting, so I did some extra research (primarily at https://books.google.com/books?id=OqUBUgW_Ax8C&pg=PA287&lpg=PA287&dq=perfective+done&source=bl&ots=wbTjJ79RdP&sig=ACfU3U3I14iqazzKpvrU1J82-vHEnvNDXQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiOzumpiNbvAhUQVd8KHfEVDVQQ6AEwDHoECBgQAw#v=onepage&q=perfective%2520done&f=false - page 287-288) and found that at least one scholar considered the perfective done to be a mark of the working class as recently as the late 1970s. In a small study, they found the construction to be used by around 2/3 of working class individuals in the south (leaving implicit that it was less common among other classes). I imagine this is largely due to the structure of neighborhoods in the United States and elsewhere, where most people live in the same neighborhoods (and, consequently, go to the same schools, grocery stores, etc) as others of a similar class. I wonder if this indicates that environmental influences are more powerful in shaping a person's dialect than cultural ones (ie television, books, etc) since people in a variety of communities tend to watch many of the same shows, read some of the same books, etc but still have substantially different dialects.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
